From: voorhisd@news.brandonu.ca
Subject: Re: NT versus Linux
Date: 7 Sep 93 11:08:10 CST

The fact that these arguments exist, and the fact that all sides have
valid points should make my point obvious:  NT, Linux, DOS, Windows,
(and VMS, TSO, CP/M, etc., etc... :-) all have their places.  There are
undoubtably SPECIFIC instances where DOS is a better choice than Linux,
and others where Linux is better than DOS, and where NT is better than
Windows, others where... You get the idea.  There is, however, no
overwhelmingly 'right' operating system, nor overwhelmingly 'wrong'
one, for ALL purposes.  (If operating systems were vehicles, some of
the past threads would be very close to the obviously silly: "A car is
better than a truck.  Everyone should have a car...")

Rather than categorically slamming NT, Windows, Linux, DOS, or
whatever, I should think an enlightened attitude would be to learn as
much as possible about every operating system or environment.   An
individual with this attitude can hopefully swallow his/her philophical
objections to particular environments or companies, and can objectively
choose the best solution for a given problem.

Since not all environments are available to everyone, I would hope this
thread would attract more (I'm not saying there haven't been any...)
responses from individuals with experience in implementing 'real world'
solutions in Linux AND Windows, or Linux AND NT, or UNIX AND NT, etc.,
and who could OBJECTIVELY compare them, feature for feature, for the
benefit of those of us who must make informed choices and
recommendations.


